## MCP Authentication Pattern

The most relevant use case for Rocket projects: let AI agents authenticate as real users
and access user data with RLS enforced.

### Using FastMCP with Supabase OAuth
```typescript
// MCP server that authenticates users via Supabase OAuth
// supabase/functions/mcp-server/index.ts
import { FastMCP } from 'fastmcp'
import { createClient } from 'jsr:@supabase/supabase-js@2'

const mcp = new FastMCP({
  name: 'My App MCP',
  version: '1.0.0',
  authenticate: async (request) => {
    // FastMCP extracts Bearer token from Authorization header
    const token = request.headers.get('authorization')?.replace('Bearer ', '')
    if (!token) throw new Error('Unauthorized')

    // Validate token with Supabase
    const supabase = createClient(
      Deno.env.get('SUPABASE_URL')!,
      Deno.env.get('SUPABASE_ANON_KEY')!,
      { global: { headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } } }
    )

    const { data: { user }, error } = await supabase.auth.getUser()
    if (error || !user) throw new Error('Unauthorized')

    return { user, token }  // passed to tool handlers
  }
})

// Tool — RLS enforced because we use the user's token
mcp.addTool({
  name: 'get_my_orders',
  description: 'Get the authenticated user\'s orders',
  execute: async (args, context) => {
    const { token } = context.auth
    const supabase = createClient(url, anonKey, {
      global: { headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } }
    })

    // RLS applies — user only sees their own orders
    const { data } = await supabase.from('orders').select('*')
    return data
  }
})
```

### Cursor / Claude MCP connection with user auth
```json
// .cursor/mcp.json — user authenticates via browser OAuth flow
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "my-app": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@your-org/my-app-mcp"],
      "env": {
        "SUPABASE_URL": "https://[REF].supabase.co",
        "OAUTH_CLIENT_ID": "your-mcp-client-id"
      }
    }
  }
}
// When Cursor starts the MCP, it opens a browser for the user to sign in
// Returns an access token — subsequent tool calls use it with RLS
```

