## RLS With OAuth 2.1 Tokens

OAuth 2.1 tokens are JWTs — RLS works exactly the same as with regular Supabase auth.

```sql
-- Standard RLS works — token contains auth.uid()
CREATE POLICY "users_own_data" ON orders FOR ALL
USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Restrict by OAuth client (scope access by which app is calling)
-- The client_id is in the JWT azp (authorized party) claim
CREATE POLICY "only_specific_oauth_app" ON sensitive_data FOR SELECT
USING (
  auth.uid() = user_id
  AND (auth.jwt()->>'azp') = 'trusted-client-id'
);

-- Restrict by OAuth scope
CREATE POLICY "require_write_scope" ON orders FOR INSERT
WITH CHECK (
  auth.uid() = user_id
  AND (auth.jwt()->'scope')::TEXT LIKE '%write:orders%'
);
```

---

## When to Use OAuth 2.1 Server

| Scenario | Use OAuth 2.1 server? |
|---|---|
| Your own Next.js app accessing Supabase | No — use supabase-js directly |
| CLI tool that authenticates users | Yes — authorization_code flow |
| AI agent (MCP) accessing user data | Yes — user authenticates once, agent uses token |
| Third-party app integrating with your platform | Yes — "Sign in with [Your App]" |
| Server-to-server (no user) | Yes — client_credentials flow |
| Another Supabase project accessing yours | No — use service_role with RLS in server code |
